  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Improving the Physical and Mental Wellbeing of Refugees in Turkey</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">As explained in Section 6.7, International Medical Corps UK will implement the action using its US affiliate International Medical Corps, with whom it works closely on numerous projects. Throughout our proposal, the term &quot;IMC&quot; refers to either this joint collaboration between International Medical Corps UK and International Medical Corps or, in the case of certain past projects with US donors, to International Medical Corps. The project aims to improve the quality of life of refugees with physical disabilities/injuries (1), to improve the physical wellbeing through provision of center or home (through mobile unit) based physical rehabilitation services, (2), psychosocial wellbeing of the rehabilitation and other clients through provision of integrated MHPSS services, (3) and to improve the capacity of local partners and other service providers in delivering quality programing to refugees in Turkey.The proposed action will provide 39,187&#xA0;services to the most vulnerable refugees and service providers in Antakya and Mersin.&#xA0;To integrate social cohesion within the activities, the action will include services for the vulnerable host community. Comprehensive rehabilitation and MHPSS services will be provided at three centers, while the mobile units attached to each center will provide services to identified patients that suffer from mobility or cannot reach the centers for various reasons. Patients requiring additional services will be referred to case workers to facilitate the provision of those services. For comprehensive protection services, IMC will closely collaborate with Danish Refugee Council and other protection actors. There will be referrals to national health services that are available under temporary protection through informative sessions, counseling and accompaniment.&#xA0;Due to the closure of the PTR Centers in Mersin by the Provincial Department of Health, only Antakya PTR Center will deliver the services from Feb to Aug 2020.</narrative>
  </description>
